Such a mass of work so rapidly produced could hardly be original, and in fact it made no claim to be so. lt was designed as a sort of encyclo aedia llos pphilosohy for Roman readers. Cicero’s plan was to take each chief department of thought in turn, and present the theories of the leading schools upon it, appending to each theory the criticisms of its opponents. Nor had his work that degree of inde- pendence which consists in assimilating the thought of others and recasting it in the mould of the writer’s own mind.
